SIMPLE: transubstantiate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transubstantiate
<hw>Tran`sub*stan"ti*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>transubstantiatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>transubstantiare</ets> to
transubstantiate; L. <ets>trans</ets> across, over +
<ets>substantia</ets> substance. See <er>Substance</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To change into another substance.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The spider love which <qex>transubstantiates</qex> all,⟦br⟧
And can convert manna to gall.</q> <rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Theol.)</fld> <def>To change, as the
sacramental elements, bread and wine, into the flesh and blood of
Christ.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transubstantiation</ent>⟦br⟧
